{
  "text": "Dysfunctional genetic variants of the G-protein \u24243 subunit 3 (GNB3, that is principally linked to G i activation), the \u2423 subunit of G s (GNAS1), [CITATION_1] and the G protein receptor kinase GRK4 [CITATION_2] (GRK4\u2425 that predominantly impacts on G s -mediated function) have been proposed as potential genetic regulators of GPCR-mediated vascular function with implications in hypertension (Figure) . The current article by Riddle et al, [CITATION_3] published in this issue of Hypertension, proposes an additional candidate gene-regulator of G-protein signaling-2 (RGS2).",
  "citation_candidates": [
